When a discovered plugin manifest lacks an 'id' field, the runtime validation silently excludes it from the plugin registry - it returns null for that manifest record rather than throwing an error. This means the plugin will not be discoverable or executable as a bundled plugin. The consequence is that any code attempting to access the plugin's public surface will receive a rejection with reason 'no bundled plugin manifest found' instead of finding the expected plugin.

